Verum eyo, ut haerentes, &za—Agamemnon speaks, and refers to the well-known story respecting the sacrifice of his daughter. Adverso litore. “ On an adverse shore.'' -206. Divos. The common account assigns the adverse winds, which detained the Grecian fleet, to the instrumentality of Diana alone : here, however, the allusion is not only to Diana, but to the other deities, who are supposed to have been requested by Diana, and to have aided her in the accomplishment of her wishes.
